title: node: make streams generic
body:
Reopen #26410

## Motivation

1. Given the fact that `Readable` stream [became](https://github.com/nodejs/node/commit/61b4d60c5d) `AsyncIterable` in Node v10.0.0, I expect `for-await-of` way of iterating over streams to become more popular. As a result people may start using native streams more often. And probably they will be using the streams with their own data types (i.e. in object mode), so it will be great to check these data types.
2. There is no type support for streams in object mode. The only type streams operate is `string | Buffer` or `any`

## Use case

My use case is iterating over documents returned by MongoDB. So I could write

```ts
const docs = db.collection<MyDataType>('...').find();
// docs is Cursor<MyDataType>, which extends Readable stream
for await (const doc of docs) {
  // I expect doc to be MyDataType here, but it is string | Buffer at the moment
}
```

title: webpack: depend on @types/tapable@^1.0.0
body:
The issue in https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/issues/24239 is that it's possible to run into a situation where your project depends on both `@types/webpack@^4` and `@types/tapable@^0` at the same time. Example here: https://github.com/elliottsj/rush-pnpm-types-test

This example is a monorepo project using [rush](https://rushjs.io/) and [pnpm](https://pnpm.js.org/). Due to the way rush and pnpm work, the package bar-webpack-plugin ends up depending on `@types/webpack@^4` and `@types/tapable@^0`. This is valid behaviour from the perspective of rush and pnpm because `@types/webpack` can depend on _any_ version of `@types/tapable`.

By instead having `@types/webpack` specify a minimum version of `@types/tapable`, pnpm will respect that constraint and install the correct version of tapable.

title: Lodash: `fp.pickBy`: incorrect inference when predicate has type guard
body:
See the failing test.

``` ts
const mixedDictionary: _.Dictionary<string | number> | null | undefined = anything;

fp.pickBy((item: string | number): item is number => typeof item === "number")(mixedDictionary); // $ExpectType Dictionary<number>

// Workaround
fp.pickBy<_.Dictionary<string | number>, number>((item: string | number): item is number => typeof item === "number")(mixedDictionary); // $ExpectType Dictionary<number>
```

This fails with:

```
Error: /Users/OliverJAsh/Development/DefinitelyTyped/types/lodash/lodash-tests.ts:5665:5
ERROR: 5665:5  expect  Expected type to be:
  Dictionary<number>
got:
  Dictionary<string | number>
```

These are the generated overloads for `fp.pickBy`:  https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/91f8a6b7d1ef61cc543d0901dcc004b846283345/types/lodash/fp.d.ts#L2889

TypeScript is using the 4th overload:

``` ts
<T>(predicate: lodash.ValueKeyIteratee<T>): LodashPickBy2x1<T>;
```

When I believe we want it to use the 1st:

``` ts
<T extends object, S extends T[keyof T]>(predicate: lodash.ValueIteratorTypeGuard<T[keyof T], S>): LodashPickBy1x1<T, S>;
```

However, this overload isn't used because `T` cannot be inferred—because the object is not passed to this higher order function.

I'm able to fix the test by rewriting the overload to:

``` ts
<T, S extends T>(predicate: lodash.ValueIteratorTypeGuard<T, S>): LodashPickBy1x1<lodash.Dictionary<T>, S>;
```

However, I don't see this as an option, because these overloads are automatically generated. We don't want to change the non-FP overloads because they are fine—this only applies to the generated FP overloads.

/cc @aj-r Any ideas what options we have here?

title: [whatwg-streams] Fixes for readable byte streams
body:
This PR makes the type definitions for readable byte streams match the spec more closely. An overview of the changes:
* `ReadableByteStreamController.enqueue` accepts any `ArrayBufferView`.  
[Step 5](https://streams.spec.whatwg.org/#rbs-controller-enqueue) only requires `chunk` to have a `[[ViewedArrayBuffer]]` internal slot, which exactly matches [`ArrayBuffer.isView`](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html#sec-arraybuffer.isview). Different chunks can have different types, as long as each of them is *some* kind of `ArrayBufferView`.
* `ReadableStreamBYOBRequest.view` is always a `Uint8Array`.  
[Step 2b](https://streams.spec.whatwg.org/#rbs-controller-byob-request) always constructs a `Uint8Array`. It will never be a different kind of `ArrayBufferView`.
* `ReadableByteStreamController.byobRequest` may be `undefined`.  
[Step 2](https://streams.spec.whatwg.org/#rbs-controller-byob-request) only constructs a BYOB request when `[[pendingPullIntos]]` is not empty. If it is empty, no BYOB request is constructed.
* Remove unused type parameter on `ReadableByteStreamSource` and related classes.  
As demonstrated by the above changes, readable byte streams aren't generic according to the spec, so there's no use for the `R` type parameter.

I've also included a small ergonomic fix for users targeting ES5:
* Replace `IteratorResult` with own interface to avoid dependency on ES2015 types.  
Previously, we used `IteratorResult<T>` in the return type of `read()`, but this type is not available when compiling with `--lib es5`. I've added a `ReadResult<T>` type which is just a copy of `IteratorResult<T>`, so the type definitions also work in ES5. 😄

- this `MeshMaterial` type had no documentation;
- `Line`, `LineSegments` and `Points` would then need a same consistent approach (`Sprite` can only have one material ?).

The original motivation is of course better type guarding. I am not aware of any feedback so far though, and these are breaking changes. It is possible that all this looks overkill also, and we may not want to get this improved type casting and rather go back to the more lenient `Material | Material[]` that was there before. 

If this is something that does benefit the community, then this PR completes the move, with a clearer `MeshMaterialType`, along with `LineMaterialType` and `PointsMaterialType`, with their respective documentation.

Original source of the issue: https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/issues/24573

Background for this change:
React Native is using same geolocation api as the browser: https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/geolocation Also react-native types depend on dom(browser) types. react-native types had typed Geolocation without problems. Now when upgrading from TS 2.7.2 -> 2.8.1 dom types have added geolocation too to the navigator object: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/compare/v2.7.2%E2%80%A6v2.8.1

So now there is a conflict since BOTH dom and react-native are defining global navigator.

Possible solutions:
1. Remove dom types 🔴 cant because react-native uses dom types (and many other libraries that you can use with react-native)
2. extend navigator object and override properties 🔴 cant because in TS you can only merge types but not override
3. Remove geolocation types from react-native(this PR) 🔵 we could do this since geolocation api should be almost same as in browser. This is the reason they did it like this that the api is the same
4. Remove navigator from global namespace in react native itself and make it as normal import 🔵 maybe but of course this would need breaking changes to the actual source code, not just types.

What do you guys think?
